<!-- ── FAQ ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<section class="py-32 max-md:py-20" id="faq">
  <div class="layout-wrap">
    <div class="fi mb-16 opacity-0 translate-y-[18px] transition-[opacity,transform] duration-[650ms] ease-out [&.in]:translate-y-0 [&.in]:opacity-100">
      <div class="mb-3.5 text-[10px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-text-kicker before:text-[rgba(139,124,255,0.62)] before:content-['//_']">FAQ</div>
      <h2 class="mb-5 font-display text-[clamp(30px,3.5vw,50px)] font-bold leading-[1.02] tracking-[-0.06em]">Common<br><em class="not-italic text-accent">questions.</em></h2>
    </div>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-x-12 gap-y-10">
      <div class="fi opacity-0 translate-y-[18px] transition-[opacity,transform] delay-100 duration-[650ms] ease-out [&.in]:translate-y-0 [&.in]:opacity-100">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-text mb-3">Do I need to be a programmer to use this?</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-text-dim leading-[1.75]">
          Not at all! While Chain Hub currently uses a command-line interface for setup, the "knowledge" you store is just simple Markdown files (like what you write in Notion or Obsidian). Once set up, you mostly just edit those text files.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fi opacity-0 translate-y-[18px] transition-[opacity,transform] delay-100 duration-[650ms] ease-out [&.in]:translate-y-0 [&.in]:opacity-100">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-text mb-3">Is my data safe and private?</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-text-dim leading-[1.75]">
          Yes. Chain Hub is "local-first," meaning all your instructions and knowledge are stored on your own computer. We don't have a cloud where your data is uploaded. You own your knowledge.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fi opacity-0 translate-y-[18px] transition-[opacity,transform] delay-200 duration-[650ms] ease-out [&.in]:translate-y-0 [&.in]:opacity-100">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-text mb-3">Which AI tools does this work with?</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-text-dim leading-[1.75]">
          Supported tools include <strong class="text-text">Claude Code</strong>, <strong class="text-text">Cursor</strong>, <strong class="text-text">Windsurf</strong>, <strong class="text-text">Gemini CLI</strong>, <strong class="text-text">Antigravity</strong>, <strong class="text-text">Kiro</strong>, <strong class="text-text">Trae</strong>, and <strong class="text-text">Mistral Vibe</strong> — plus a universal <span class="whitespace-nowrap rounded-[5px] border border-accent/25 bg-accent/10 px-1.5 py-px font-mono text-[11px] text-code-inline">~/.agents/</span> fallback. We keep adding integrations as new assistants ship.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fi opacity-0 translate-y-[18px] transition-[opacity,transform] delay-200 duration-[650ms] ease-out [&.in]:translate-y-0 [&.in]:opacity-100">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-text mb-3">Does it cost anything?</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-text-dim leading-[1.75]">
          Chain Hub is <strong class="text-text">open-source and free to use</strong>. You can install it and use it for your personal or professional projects without any subscription fees.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fi opacity-0 translate-y-[18px] transition-[opacity,transform] delay-300 duration-[650ms] ease-out [&.in]:translate-y-0 [&.in]:opacity-100">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-text mb-3">How do I update my knowledge?</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-text-dim leading-[1.75]">
          Just open the files in your Hub folder, make your changes, and save. Chain Hub ensures that all your AI tools see the latest version of that file immediately. No more copy-pasting!
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fi opacity-0 translate-y-[18px] transition-[opacity,transform] delay-300 duration-[650ms] ease-out [&.in]:translate-y-0 [&.in]:opacity-100">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-bold text-text mb-3">What is a Skill vs an Agent vs a Workflow?</h3>
        <p class="text-xs text-text-dim leading-[1.75]">
          A <strong class="text-text">Skill</strong> is playbook-style knowledge for your main assistant (when to use it, steps, outputs).
          An <strong class="text-text">Agent</strong> is a separate worker definition for a focused sub-session (e.g. a deep review).
          A <strong class="text-text">Workflow</strong> is a procedure document—often a checklist for you or your team, with the AI helping along the way.
          See the <a href="#skills-agents-workflows" class="font-medium text-[rgba(139,124,255,0.62)] no-underline hover:underline">Skills, agents &amp; workflows</a> section on this page for a compact comparison table.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
